<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1050,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1230,1256]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[353,457,1230,1256]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete with eight thoracic and 28 abdominal chaetigers. Body length 
<quantity box="[1284,1374,1230,1257]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
, with crown 
<quantity box="[228,313,1266,1293]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
long, and 
<quantity box="[429,515,1266,1293]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
wide. Body light brown coloured on ventral side and with flattened abdomen (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1508,1532]" captionTargetBox="[155,1422,191,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-27@12.[151,1436,181,1484]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636151" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636151/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
). Crown with five pairs of radioles with 12 pairs of pinnules of medium length each, arranged in two longitudinal rows with a small space gap between the pinnules of the same pair, and with space increasing at the base of the radiole. The pinnules appear longer in median position where they measure 1/4 of the total radiolar length, and becoming considerably shorter towards the end of the radiole. Tip of radiole long, slender and pointed (
<figureCitation box="[1333,1423,1410,1436]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1508,1532]" captionTargetBox="[155,1422,191,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-27@12.[151,1436,181,1484]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636151" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636151/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
). Dorsal lips measuring 1/5 of the total radiolar length.Anterior peristomial ring not visible. Posterior peristomial ring higher ventrally with a mid-ventral incision where low ventral basal flanges attach, extending as prominent ridges from base of ventral-most radioles (
<figureCitation box="[552,674,1518,1545]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1508,1532]" captionTargetBox="[155,1422,191,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-27@12.[151,1436,181,1484]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636151" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636151/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 8D, E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1050,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">
Small brown peristomial eyes present. Pygidial eyes present as clusters of red spots on lateral margins of pygidium. Thorax longer than wide. First thoracic chaetiger with only 3 chaetae similar in shape to the superior chaetae of the following chaetigers. From the second to the eighth thoracic chaetiger, 5 uncini on each torus. Thoracic uncini with rounded and flattened breast, with four rows of teeth above main fang, and with handles long approximately 1/3 of the total uncinus length (0.35) so considered between medium and short length (
<figureCitation box="[1108,1197,1698,1724]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
). Companion chaetae present, with straight shaft and long mucro (
<figureCitation box="[643,731,1734,1760]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). Thoracic chaetae from second to eighth chaetigers, number 4, of which one superior broadly-hooded chaeta (
<figureCitation box="[680,769,1770,1796]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
) and three paleate chaetae in inferior row with mucro long as the hood (
<figureCitation box="[294,381,1806,1832]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9E</figureCitation>
). Abdominal uncini in number of 3, with similar-sized small teeth above the main fang, higher than the thoracic one and with short handle (
<figureCitation box="[673,764,1842,1868]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
). Three abdominal neurochaetae thin and broadly hooded, similar to paleate of the thorax but longer in the first abdominal segments (
<figureCitation box="[986,1074,1878,1904]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
) and becoming longer and more geniculate starting from mid abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[594,684,1914,1940]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1577,1601]" captionTargetBox="[186,1402,246,1538]" captionTargetId="figure-55@13.[172,1414,236,1553]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636154/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 9H</figureCitation>
). Spermathechae present brown/red coloured.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1050,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,396,1950,1976]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Staining pattern.</emphasis>
In both thorax and abdomen stain only ventral shields. Peristomium, thorax and abdomen showing an intense colouration in the central part, but with a pattern covering most of the segment width (
<figureCitation box="[1251,1337,1986,2012]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1508,1532]" captionTargetBox="[155,1422,191,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-27@12.[151,1436,181,1484]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Amphiglena nisidensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636151" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636151/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636151" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4636151" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636151/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" startId="12.[151,250,1508,1532]" targetBox="[155,1422,191,1478]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,1508,1568]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1508,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">FIGURE 8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[282,510,1508,1532]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nisidensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[282,510,1508,1532]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">Amphiglena nisidensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[517,597,1508,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[517,541,1508,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">sp</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[554,597,1508,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[603,621,1508,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">A</emphasis>
. entire worm, photo from the holotype; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1029,1053,1508,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">B.</emphasis>
staining pattern; 
